      <h4>Low input conservation headlands</h4>
      <img src="images/option_34B.png">
      <p>Some more robust arable flowers, such as <a href="#species/26">cornflower</a>, <a href="#species/100">shepherds-needle</a>
        and <a href="#species/94">corn buttercup</a>, will thrive within modern cereal crop
        headlands PROVIDED there is no fertiliser applied and there is restricted
        use of herbicides (see Scheme rules). These habitats also provide good
        cover for game birds and plentiful insects to feed them. If left unharvested,
        the seeds provide plentiful food for farmland birds in winter too. A
        useful practical tip is to sow a reduced rate of cereal on the headland
        to produce a more open crop for the cornfield flowers, and save money.
        Below is a summary of some of the options under agri-environment schemes
        to provide this habitat:   </p>

