      <h4>Whole crop cereals/roots</h4>
      <img src="images/option_30.png">
      <img src="images/option_32.png">
      <p>Less intensive management of crops on a field scale can also benefit
        arable flowers. This is particularly suitable where root crops are grown
        for livestock feed over the winter, such as beet, or spring sown cereals
        with peas are grown for whole crop silage. Plants that grow in this type
        of arable habitat include more robust species like
        <a href="#species/26">cornflower</a>,
        <a href="#species/61">corn marigold</a>,
        <a href="#species/83">weasel’s-snout</a> and <a href="#species/34"> purple bugloss.</a>.
        Below is a summary of some of the
